                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d382">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 837.00/760.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Special Representative of President Gómez</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-06-15">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 15, 1912</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Ferrara</hi>: In reply to your note of the 13th
                    instant, wherein you suggest that to calm the unrest of the people in Cuba an
                    additional statement be made by the American Minister at Habana concerning the
                    real attitude of the Government of the United States, I take pleasure in
                    enclosing copy of a statement<note n="1" xml:id="d382fn1">Contained in the
                        instruction of June 14, 3 p.m.</note> which the American minister was
                    authorized to make public yesterday.</p>
                <p>I am [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">P. C. Knox</hi>.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
